Strengths and weaknesses with different sensors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
GPS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Global Positioning System - GPS is used to determine the global coordinates
 of a device in latitudes and longitudes through the use of satellites
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NCOSBPNT2014"

\end_inset

.
 The 24 satellites that are being used for this are put out in six different
 orbits circulating the earth in a manner that assures visibility of at
 least five of them no matter of time and location on the earth
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bajaj2002"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To establish locations of devices the satellites continuously send out pseudoran
dom number codes (PNC).
 Each PNC consists of information of the satellite's position and time at
 the moment of transmission.
 When acquiring a PNC, its travel time is calculated by the GPS receiver
 by subtracting the departure time from the arrival time.
 A PNC travels at the speed of light(c), which in combination with the travel
 time(t) is enough information to calculate the distance(x) between the
 satellite and receiver
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bajaj2002"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x=c\cdot\triangle t$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hewitt2006"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x=c\cdot(t_{arrival}-t_{departure})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Location wise, this distance does however only determine that the GPS receiver
 is located somewhere at the surface on a sphere with the radius being the
 distance and the center being the satellite.
 To acquire the GPS receiver's location on the sphere, the method trilateration
 as shown in XXXX is used.
 
\end_layout

